C. Excision Malignant Lesion & MarginsClinical Diagnosis: Excised Squamous Cell Carcinoma Location: Right Arm
Method: Excision
Lesion Size: 1.1 x 1.2 cm
Excision Size, including margins: 2.1 x 2.2 cm
The patient was evaluated preoperative and noted to be in stable condition. 
 Informed consent was obtained from the patient. All risks, benefits, and alternatives regarding the survey have been reviewed in detail with the patient. 
 This includes risks of bleeding, infection, scarring recurrence of lesion and need for further procedures. 
After consent was obtained, attention was turned toward the area of interest which was disinfected and cleaned with alcohol. Local anesthetic, 2% lidocaine with epinephrine was infiltrated around the site. An elliptical incision with the appropriate margins was made using a Number 15 to obtain a full thickness specimen. Dissection of the surrounding/overlying tissue was performed to isolate, expose and remove the lesion. The specimen was placed in a bottle labeled C. #MAD24-845. 
Repair: Layered Closure 
The wound was closed with an intermediate layered closure on 12-17-2024. The wound involved the dermis and subcutaneous tissue which required a layer repair to minimize tension and promote optimal healing. The closure was performed in two layers; the deep dermis/ subcutaneous layer was approximated utilizing 4-O Vicryl absorbable sutures while the epidermal layer was closed with the use of 4-O Nylon sutures. 
This layered closure was necessary due to the wounds depth and tissue separation. The location of the wound required reinforcement with a deep dermal closure to prevent breakdown and minimize risk of wound complications. The final closure size is 3.9 cm. 
Pressure was applied to achieve hemostasis. Bacitracin was applied at the wound site and it was bandaged. Patient tolerated the procedure well and wound care instructions were reviewed and given to the patient.
