2026-04-27 13:26:31.087 | INFO     | app.services.medical_engine:parse:153 - 🧾 biopsyNotes AFTER CLEAN: A. Excision Malignant Lesion & Margins
Clinical Diagnosis: EX SCC
Location: Mid Chest
Method: Excision
Lesion Size: 3.0 - 2.0 cm
Excision Size, including margins: 3.5 x 4.0 cm
The patient was evaluated preoperative and noted to be in stable condition. 
 Informed consent was obtained from the patient. All risks, benefits, and alternatives regarding the survey have been reviewed in detail with the patient. 
 This includes risks of bleeding, infection, scarring recurrence of lesion and need for further procedures. 
After consent was obtained, attention was turned toward the area of interest which was disinfected and cleaned with alcohol. Local anesthetic, 2% lidocaine with epinephrine was infiltrated around the site. An elliptical incision with the appropriate margins was made using a Number 15 to obtain a full thickness specimen. Dissection of the surrounding/overlying tissue was performed to isolate, expose and remove the lesion. The specimen was placed in a bottle labeled A. #WC24-542. 
Repair: Complex Closure 
The wound was closed with a complex closure on 05-06-2024. The wound size with margins is 3.5 - 4.0 cm. 
Complex repair was performed because the defect extended into of the deep subcutaneous tissue and superficial non-muscular fascia. Extensive wide undermining was performed to a distance of 4 cm (defect width perpendicular to closure is 4 cm) along the edge of the entire surgical defect to mobilize adjacent tissue, reduce wound tension and minimize the distortion of the adjacent functional structure.
Buried, absorbable retention sutures were placed to close the deep subcutaneous tissue and superficial non-muscular fascia. Retention suture placement was necessary: to avoid deforming, a depressed and contracted scar, anatomic distortion and functional deficit in adjacent fixed structures, injury to tendons and nerves in the area, to ensure proper range of motion, maintain function in the area, preserve the normal anatomy, reduce subcutaneous dead space to reduce the risk of hematoma, to reduce tension to skin to allow closure, and to reduce the risk of necrosis, infection and wound dehiscence.
The deep subcutaneous tissue, superficial non-muscular fascia and dermis was closed with 4-O Vicryl sutures followed by meticulous epidermal approximation.Epidermal closure was achieved with 4-O Nylon sutures.
Closure necessitated advanced layered techniques beyond a routine intermediate repair due to the defect size, depth, and location. The final closure size was 5.5 cm.
Pressure was applied to achieve hemostasis. Bacitracin was applied at the wound site and it was bandaged. Patient tolerated the procedure well and wound care instructions were reviewed and given to the patient.
2026-04-27 13:26:34.116 | INFO     | app.services.medical_engine:retrieve:181 - 🧠 Retrieval Decision | Parsed: {'has_biopsy': False, 'biopsy_count': 0, 'biopsy_sections': [], 'has_excision': True, 'excision_sections': [{'label': 'A', 'text': 'A. Excision Malignant Lesion & Margins\nClinical Diagnosis: EX SCC\nLocation: Mid Chest\nMethod: Excision\nLesion Size: 3.0 - 2.0 cm\nExcision Size, including margins: 3.5 x 4.0 cm\nThe patient was evaluated preoperative and noted to be in stable condition. \n Informed consent was obtained from the patient. All risks, benefits, and alternatives regarding the survey have been reviewed in detail with the patient. \n This includes risks of bleeding, infection, scarring recurrence of lesion and need for further procedures. \nAfter consent was obtained, attention was turned toward the area of interest which was disinfected and cleaned with alcohol. Local anesthetic, 2% lidocaine with epinephrine was infiltrated around the site. An elliptical incision with the appropriate margins was made using a Number 15 to obtain a full thickness specimen. Dissection of the surrounding/overlying tissue was performed to isolate, expose and remove the lesion. The specimen was placed in a bottle labeled A. #WC24-542.', 'size': 4.0, 'quantity': 1}], 'has_mohs': True, 'mohs_sections': [{'label': 'single', 'text': 'Location: Left Temple\nPre-op Diagnosis: Lentigo Maligna\nPathology Reference: WC24-00419\nMohs Log: 5686\nIn an informative discussion of the mohs procedure, the nature of the skin cancer, \n alternative treatment options, consequences of no treatment and convalescence were reviewed with the patient. \n The risks and benefits, including but not limited to: bleeding, spread of infection, pain, scarring, bruising, \n distortion of the surrounding areas, allergic reaction to the medications used, recurrence of the tumor, \n and opening of the wound were discussed and understood by the patient. \nAll questions from the patient were answered adequately. \n No guarantees were given and the patient was informed that Mohs surgery is indicated to provide \n the highest cure rate by excising the tissue in multiple stages and preserving the healthy tissue as much as possible. \nAfter obtaining informed consent, the patient was given a mirror and \n corroborated the location of the tumor prior to surgery. \n Mohs Micrographic Procedure:\nAttention was turned toward the surgical site, which was disinfected and cleansed with alcohol. The patient was draped using a sterile technique. Local anesthetic lidocaine 1 % with epinephrine was infiltrated around the site. The procedure was performed in accordance with the Mohs micrographic surgical technique. \n The tumor site was debulk prior to the first Mohs stage. With each stage, a thin layer of tissue was excised with a narrow margin of normal appearing skin using the Mohs fresh tissue technique. Hemostasis was achieved with Pressure. The surgical site was dressed with gauze pressure dressings and the patient remained in the surgical area. The tissue was prepared for the cryostat and sectioned. Each section was coded, cut and stained for microscopic examination. The slides were then analyzed by the Mohs surgeon for any evidence of remaining tumor. Areas noted to be positive on the previous stage (if applicable) were removed with the mohs technique and processed for analysis. This process was repeated until a tumor free plane was obtained. \n1st Stage: 2 Sections, Negative\nPost-Mohs Deficit Size: 2.2 x 2.3 cm.\n Repair Options:\n \n After a discussion of wound management options, \n due to the size and location of the defect, and the need to achieve optimal cosmesis, \n avoid hematoma, the following wound management was agreed upon to provide the best functional and cosmetic result. \n Performed: \n The wound was closed with a Complex Closure on the same day of mohs. \n Reconstruction:\nRepair: Complex Closure\nThe postoperative deficit was 2.2 x 2.3 cm. The wound was closed with a complex closure. The defect was undermined extensively (1 cm) to reduce tension and distortion of the adjacent structures. Buried absorbable sutures were also used to close the subcutaneous and dermal components of the defect. The wound was approximated utilizing 4-O Vicryl and 4-O Nylon sutures. \nThe final closure size is 4.5 cm. \n Post-Operative:\nThe patient tolerated the procedure well with no complications, and minimal bleeding. The wound was covered with Vaseline and Press Dressing. Detailed oral and written post-operative instructions were reviewed and given to the patient. The patient instructed to remove dressing in 24 hours, sleep with the surgical site elevated this evening, avoid alcohol, trauma and tobacco.\n Patient was informed to return in 10 Days for suture removal with Attiya Haroon MD.', 'location': 'Left Temple', 'stages': 1}], 'has_procedure': False}
