nique. Hemostasis was achieved with Pressure, Electrocautery. The surgical site was dressed with gauze pressure dressings and the patient remained in the surgical area. The tissue was prepared for the cryostat and sectioned. Each section was coded, cut and stained for microscopic examination. The slides were then analyzed by the Mohs surgeon for any evidence of remaining tumor. Areas noted to be positive on the previous stage (if applicable) were removed with the mohs technique and processed for analysis. This process was repeated until a tumor free plane was obtained. \n1st Stage: 2 Sections, Negative\nPost-Mohs Deficit Size: 1.8 x 2.1 cm.\n Repair Options:\nAfter a discussion of wound management options, due to the size and location of the defect, and the need to achieve optimal cosmesis, avoid hematoma, the following wound management was agreed upon to provide the best functional and cosmetic result.\nPerformed:\nThe wound was closed with a Complex Closure on the same day of mohs.\nReconstruction:\nRepair:\xa0Complex Closure\nThe postoperative deficit was 2.1 x 1.6 cm. The wound was closed with a complex closure. The defect extended into the deep subcutaneous tissue and superficial fascia. The wound was undermined extensively (1.0 cm) to mobilize adjacent tissue, reduce wound tension and minimize the distortion of the adjacent functional structures. Buried absorbable sutures were placed to close the subcutaneous tissue and superficial fascia, followed by meticulous epidermal approximation. Closure necessitated advanced layered techniques beyond a routine intermediate repair due to the defect size, depth, and location. The wound was approximated utilizing 4-O Vicryl and 4-O Nylon sutures.\nThe final closure size is 4.7 cm.\n \n After a discussion of wound management options, \n due to the size and location of the defect, and the need to achieve optimal cosmesis, \n avoid hematoma, the following wound management was agreed upon to provide the best functional and cosmetic result. \n Secondary Intention: \n The wound was left to heal by secondary intention after Electrodessication for homeostasis. \n Reconstruction:\n \n Post-Operative:\nThe patient tolerated the procedure well with no complications, and minimal bleeding. The wound was covered with a Press Dressing. Detailed oral and written post-operative instructions were reviewed and given to the patient. The patient instructed to remove dressing in 24 hours, sleep with the surgical site elevated this evening, avoid alcohol, trauma and tobacco.\n Patient was informed to return in 10 Days.', 'location': 'Right Cheek', 'stages': 1}], 'has_procedure': False}
