n for homeostasis.\nThe patient tolerated the procedure well with no complications, and minimal bleeding. The wound was covered with Steri Strips and Press Dressing. Detailed oral and written post-operative instructions were reviewed and given to the patient. The patient instructed to remove dressing in 24 hours, sleep with the surgical site elevated this evening, avoid alcohol, trauma and tobacco.\n Patient was informed to return in 10 Days.', 'location': 'Right Cheek', 'stages': 1}, {'label': 'site_3', 'text': 'Location: Left Jaw\nPre-op Diagnosis: Lentigo Maligna\nPathology Reference: WC25-01469\nMohs Log: 6366\nIn an informative discussion of the mohs procedure, the nature of the skin cancer, \n alternative treatment options, consequences of no treatment and convalescence were reviewed with the patient. \n The risks and benefits, including but not limited to: bleeding, spread of infection, pain, scarring, bruising, \n distortion of the surrounding areas, allergic reaction to the medications used, recurrence of the tumor, \n and opening of the wound were discussed and understood by the patient. \nAll questions from the patient were answered adequately. \n No guarantees were given and the patient was informed that Mohs surgery is indicated to provide \n the highest cure rate by excising the tissue in multiple stages and preserving the healthy tissue as much as possible. \nAfter obtaining informed consent, the patient was given a mirror and \n corroborated the location of the tumor prior to surgery. \n Mohs Micrographic Procedure:\nAttention was turned toward the surgical site, which was disinfected and cleansed with chlorhexidine. The patient was draped using a sterile technique. Local anesthetic lidocaine 1 % with epinephrine was infiltrated around the site. The procedure was performed in accordance with the Mohs micrographic surgical technique. \n The tumor site was debulk prior to the first Mohs stage. With each stage, a thin layer of tissue was excised with a narrow margin of normal appearing skin using the Mohs fresh tissue technique. Hemostasis was achieved with Pressure, Electrocautery. The surgical site was dressed with gauze pressure dressings and the patient remained in the surgical area. The tissue was prepared for the cryostat and sectioned. Each section was coded, cut and stained for microscopic examination. The slides were then analyzed by the Mohs surgeon for any evidence of remaining tumor. Areas noted to be positive on the previous stage (if applicable) were removed with the mohs technique and processed for analysis. This process was repeated until a tumor free plane was obtained. \n1st Stage: 2 Sections, Negative\nPost-Mohs Deficit Size: 1.8 x 2.1 cm.\n Repair Options:\nAfter a discussion of wound management options, due to the size and location of the defect, and the need to achieve optimal cosmesis, avoid hematoma, the following wound management was agreed upon to provide the best functional and cosmetic result.\nPerformed:\nThe wound was closed with a Complex Closure on the same day of mohs.\nReconstruction:\nRepair:\xa0Complex Closure\nThe postoperative deficit was 2.1 x 1.6 cm. The wound was closed with a complex closure. The defect extended into the deep subcutaneous tissue and superficial fascia. The wound was undermined extensively (1.0 cm) to mobilize adjacent tissue, reduce wound tension and minimize the distortion of the adjacent functional structures. Buried absorbable sutures were placed to close the subcutaneous tissue and superficial fascia, followed by meticulous epidermal approximation. Closure necessitated advanced layered techniques beyond a routine intermediate repair due to the defect size, depth, and location. The wound was approximated utilizing 4-O Vicryl and 4-O Nylon sutures.\nThe final closure size is 4.7 cm.\n \n After a discussion of wound management options, \n due to the size and location of the defect, and the need to achieve optimal cosmesis, \n avoid hematoma, the following wound management was agreed upon to provide the best functional and cosmetic result. \n Secondary Intention: \n The wound was left to heal by secondary intention after Electrodessication for homeostasis. \n Reconstruction:\n \n Post-Operative:\nThe patient tolerated the procedure well with no complications, and minimal bleeding. The wound was covered with a Press Dressing. Detailed oral and written post-operative instructions were reviewed and given to the patient. The patient instructed to remove dressing in 24 hours, sleep with the surgical site elevated this evening, avoid alcohol, trauma and tobacco.\n Patient was informed to return in 10 Days.', 'location': 'Left Jaw', 'stages': 1}], 'has_procedure': False}
