 surgical area. The tissue was prepared for the cryostat and sectioned. Each section was coded, cut and stained for microscopic examination. The slides were then analyzed by the Mohs surgeon for any evidence of remaining tumor. Areas noted to be positive on the previous stage (if applicable) were removed with the mohs technique and processed for analysis. This process was repeated until a tumor free plane was obtained. \n1st Stage: 2 Sections, Negative\nPost-Mohs Deficit Size: 1.9 x 1.6 cm.\n Repair Options:\n \n After a discussion of wound management options, \n due to the size and location of the defect, and the need to achieve optimal cosmesis, \n avoid hematoma, the following wound management was agreed upon to provide the best functional and cosmetic result. \n Performed: \n The wound was closed with a Complex Closure on the same day of mohs. \n Reconstruction:\nThe wound was closed with a complex closure on 03-11-2026. The surgical defect size is 1.9 x 1.6 cm.\nComplex repair was performed because the defect extended into of the deep subcutaneous tissue and superficial non-muscular fascia. Extensive wide undermining was performed to a distance of 1.9 cm (defect width perpendicular to closure is 1.9 cm) along the edge of the entire surgical defect to mobilize adjacent tissue, reduce wound tension and minimize the distortion of the adjacent functional structure.\nBuried, absorbable retention sutures were placed to close the deep subcutaneous tissue and superficial non-muscular fascia. Retention suture placement was necessary: to avoid deforming, a depressed and contracted scar, anatomic distortion and functional deficit in adjacent fixed structures, injury to tendons and nerves in the area, to ensure proper range of motion, maintain function in the area, preserve the normal anatomy, reduce subcutaneous dead space to reduce the risk of hematoma, to reduce tension to skin to allow closure, and to reduce the risk of necrosis, infection and wound dehiscence.\nThe deep subcutaneous tissue, superficial non-muscular fascia and dermis was closed with 3-O Vicryl sutures followed by meticulous epidermal approximation.Epidermal closure was achieved with 3-O Nylon sutures.\nClosure necessitated advanced layered techniques beyond a routine intermediate repair due to the defect size, depth, and location.The final closure size was 4.4 cm. \n Post-Operative:\nThe patient tolerated the procedure well with no complications, and minimal bleeding. The wound was covered with Vaseline and Press Dressing. Detailed oral and written post-operative instructions were reviewed and given to the patient. The patient instructed to remove dressing in 24 hours, sleep with the surgical site elevated this evening, avoid alcohol, trauma and tobacco.\n Patient was informed to return in 3 Months.', 'location': 'Right Temple', 'stages': 1}], 'has_procedure': True}
