2026-04-27 18:34:28.334 | INFO     | app.services.medical_engine:parse:153 - 🧾 biopsyNotes AFTER CLEAN: A. Excision Malignant Lesion & Margins
Clinical Diagnosis: EXC SCC
Location: Right Upper Back
Method: Excision
Lesion Size: 1.3 x 0.8 cm
Excision Size, including margins: 2.3 x 1.8 cm
The patient was evaluated preoperative and noted to be in stable condition. 
 Informed consent was obtained from the patient. All risks, benefits, and alternatives regarding the survey have been reviewed in detail with the patient. 
 This includes risks of bleeding, infection, scarring recurrence of lesion and need for further procedures. 
After consent was obtained, attention was turned toward the area of interest which was disinfected and cleaned with alcohol. Local anesthetic, 1% lidocaine with epinephrine was infiltrated around the site. An elliptical incision with the appropriate margins was made using a Number 15 to obtain a full thickness specimen. Dissection of the surrounding/overlying tissue was performed to isolate, expose and remove the lesion. The specimen was placed in a bottle labeled A. #RA25-1480. 
Repair: Complex Closure 
The wound was closed with a complex closure on 08-11-2025. The wound size with margins is 2.3 - 1.8 cm. 
Complex repair was performed because the defect extended into of the deep subcutaneous tissue and superficial non-muscular fascia. Extensive wide undermining was performed to a distance of 2.3 cm (defect width perpendicular to closure is 2.3 cm) along the edge of the entire surgical defect to mobilize adjacent tissue, reduce wound tension and minimize the distortion of the adjacent functional structure.
Buried, absorbable retention sutures were placed to close the deep subcutaneous tissue and superficial non-muscular fascia. Retention suture placement was necessary: to avoid deforming, a depressed and contracted scar, anatomic distortion and functional deficit in adjacent fixed structures, injury to tendons and nerves in the area, to ensure proper range of motion, maintain function in the area, preserve the normal anatomy, reduce subcutaneous dead space to reduce the risk of hematoma, to reduce tension to skin to allow closure, and to reduce the risk of necrosis, infection and wound dehiscence.
The deep subcutaneous tissue, superficial non-muscular fascia and dermis was closed with 3-O Vicryl sutures followed by meticulous epidermal approximation.Epidermal closure was achieved with 3-O Nylon sutures.
Closure necessitated advanced layered techniques beyond a routine intermediate repair due to the defect size, depth, and location. The final closure size was 4.2 cm.
Pressure was applied to achieve hemostasis. Aquaphor was applied at the wound site and it was bandaged. Patient tolerated the procedure well and wound care instructions were reviewed and given to the patient.
